We are given an array of size n. Our Job is to return the element that is repeating atleast n/2 times. We have to do this in linear time.


Moore voting algorithm:

we use two variables candidate and count.

We maintain a candidate and a count. If count becomes 0, we choose the current element as the new candidate. 
If the current element is the same as the candidate, we increase count. Otherwise, we decrease count. 
Since the majority element appears more than half of the array, all other elements can cancel out some of its occurrences, but they cannot completely remove it. 
Therefore, the remaining candidate at the end is the majority element.


Algorithm:

Step 1: Start by initializing the candidate and count to 0.
Step 2: Start iterating the array. If count = 0 , current element becomes candidate.
Step 3:if current element == candidate count increments or else count decrements.
Step 4: Return the candidate.


Code:

class Solution {
    public int majorityElement(int[] nums) {

        int candidate = 0; int count =0;

        for(int i =0;i < nums.length; i++)
        {
            if(count == 0)
            {
                candidate = nums[i];
                count++;
            }
            else if(nums[i] != candidate) { count--;}
            else count++;

        }
        return candidate;
    }
}

Second Approach:

Logic: As the number is repeating n/2 times when we sort the array the number comes exactly to the center of the array. 


Algorithm:
Step 1: First sort the input array.
Step 2: Return the element at position n/2 in the array.

Solution:
class Solution {
    public int majorityElement(int[] nums) {

        Arrays.sort(nums);

        return nums[nums.length/2];
        
    }
}

Apparoach 2 :

Take a hashmap that stores number and its apperences. For every repeated number increase its apprience count. Once done return the number that is repeating n/2 times.

class Solution {
    public int majorityElement(int[] nums) {
        int n = nums.length;
        Map<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
        
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            map.put(nums[i], map.getOrDefault(nums[i], 0) + 1);
        }
        
        n = n / 2;
        for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> entry : map.entrySet()) {
            if (entry.getValue() > n) {
                return entry.getKey();
            }
        }
        
        return 0;
    }
}
